{Partner's 2\H bid is a transfer so you bid 2\S. Partner now bids 4\S and you pass. 

North plays 4\S. East leads the \C9. West takes the \CA, then returns the \C7 on which East plays the \C2.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 1 : \C = 1 :: Total = 3

Careful! Although it looks like only 3 losers you are in real danger of a \C ruff. It is almost certain that East has led a doubleton \C so if West can get the lead with either \SA or \DA they will get the ruff.  

Fortunately your \Ds are solid and you do not need the \HQ as a winner.

So before playing any trumps play \H A K, discarding dummy's \CK. That's a lot of winners you are wasting but you can afford it.  

Only then can you afford to play a \S. West can win the \SA, but if he plays a \C dummy will be able to over-ruff East.

After you pull trumps you can drive out the \DA and claim the contract.

As you see, trying even one round of trumps would have been fatal.

You had to get rid of dummy's singleton \H first - the fact that it was a winner should not affect your making the correct play.}
[Play "W"]C9

